The paper deals with the problem of decoding error-correcting codes over noisy channels, which is a fundamental problem in information theory (cs.IT). The focus is on low density parity check (LDPC) codes, which are a popular class of codes in coding theory (cs.CC). The paper also discusses the use of expander codes, which are a type of LDPC code, and their performance on binary symmetric channels (BSCs) and additive white Gaussian noise (AWGN) channels, which are topics in signal processing and communication theory (cs.SI, cs.NI). The paper also introduces a new algorithm based on the max-flow algorithm, which is a topic in algorithms and data structures (cs.DS).
